that he promised them that he was going to do just one additional term  So his now wanting to do another four years after doing six is viewed as breaking a promise  a solemn promise he had made  Copyright   2015 Virginia Military Institute  For academic and news media use only  No quotes from the materials contained herein may be used in any media without attribution to Virginia Military Institute  For other uses  contact Maj  Sherri Tombarge  540 464 7936  tombargesk vmi edu  Note  Transcripts are created on deadline  and accuracy may vary  This text may not be in its final form and may be updated or revised in the future  Please be aware that the authoritative record is the video   Pre Election Nigeria  A Dialogue Dr  Jim Hentz  Professor International Studies Dr  James Gire  Professor of Psychology Moderated by Sherri Tombarge  Director of News and Editorial Services Virginia Military Institute Jan  15  2015 Feb  14  Elections amid Unrest  Download pdf The upcoming election Feb  14 in Nigeria pits a Christian incumbent with total control over patronage of centralized oil but no control   none   over the violence of Boko Haram against a Muslim former military dictator  So is perhaps the biggest challenger in a democratic election a former dictator  Why is Goodluck Jonathan perhaps favored to win in spite of all the violence  Just what on earth is going on   social  political dynamics  currents  Hentz  The reason why it may appear that Goodluck Jonathan has an early advantage would be that he has control over the patronage resources  he has control to some extent over the media and outflow of information  so he ll use his considerable resources to make it appear as if he s the likely winner  I probably would not bet on that being the actual fact  Gire  I think I would agree with that assessment  In fact  my first thought when you floated that idea was that I didn t know that he was expected or favored to be the winner  On the contrary  many would argue that unless 